    {
      "id": 8,
      "type": "text",
      "title": "How the math works",
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 8,
        "w": 24,
        "x": 0,
        "y": 25
      },
      "options": {
        "mode": "markdown",
        "content": "## Source of truth\n\nAll four panels in **both rows** are derived from a single Prometheus metric: `firewall_rules_processed_current`. This is a **monotonic** Gauge bootstrapped from `decision_history.jsonl` on each API start, so it is restart-safe. Deriving every pound/hour/HIPS figure from one source guarantees the four panels can never disagree.\n\n## Constants (per rule)\n\n| Multiplier | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| HIPS freed | x 21 | `HIPS_FREED_PER_RULE` in `api/roi_metrics.py` |\n| Hours saved | x 42 | `HOURS_PER_RULE` |\n| Cost saved | x GBP 1,009.68 | `COST_PER_RULE` (= 42h x GBP 24.04/h) |\n| FTE redeployed | / 2080 | std working hours/year |\n\n## Why two rows\n\n- **Selected Range** uses `current - min_over_time(current[$__range])` — so picking *Last 24h* gives you exactly the last 24h of accrual. Picking *Last 7 days* gives you 7 days. The `min_over_time` form is cold-start-safe: while the metric is younger than the window, you simply see the delta over its lifetime so far.\n- **Lifetime Totals** ignore the picker — they are the all-time cumulative since the metric was first scraped. Useful for board decks; not useful for ops triage.\n\n## Update lag\n\nPrometheus scrape interval is 15s, so the dashboard reflects a rule processed within ~15-30 seconds."
      }
